The paper deals with video classification using convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and focuses on extracting spatio-temporal activity regions from compressed video bitstreams. This involves selective access to motion vector information within the bitstreams, which is then used to derive activity data at high speed. Given this, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). 

The paper also involves training two CNN architectures on MB texture and MV correspondences, which suggests a focus on multimedia (cs.MM). Additionally, the paper discusses cloud computing cost, which could indicate a focus on information retrieval (cs.IR) or machine learning (cs.LG).
